column356: I had no issues at all, thank you!
It's funny that you think that  an executive has anywhere near as much value as a doctor.
This is one of good survey. Thank you.
I love ethical situations like this! They're fun to examine, though scary to encounter in real life.
is the car able to differentiate between male and females? what if they are transgender? How does it detect what gender? based on looks or does it have some sort of special detection system?
The last question seemed a bit vague. The Robocar did not ACTUALLY kill someone correct?

Self-driving cars are SO much safer than regular cars driven by regular people. Always it seems everyone focuses on a single fatality by a self-driving car when hundreds and hundreds of people are killed every year by conventionally driven cars. Unfortunately most people don't share my opinion.
Considering how often technology malfunctions, how its prone to hacking, privacy violations, etc., I really don't understand this obsession with self driving cars.
The survey was interesting, thank you.
Not sure why there isn't human intervention involved in the RoboCar.
Weird attention check in the beginning....
robot cars need not be judge jury and executioner
All clear and easy to understand, thank you.
If funding allows please consider paying future participants more. Have a good one.

Why does such a setting have to be deliberate... just toss coin for fairness. For all I know the athlete could been a bad guy and the large person was a chef who cooked for the school to give kids a healthy lunch for free.
Would have liked to have known if the/a driver (passenger) could have taken over control in such a situation.
Not at this time - but thank you.
Regardless of it being a robocar or not the person driving needs to pay attention to what is around them
no technical issues with the survey
regarding the attention check at the beginning: the sliders were pretty touchy--I believe that I set them correctly initially, but when I checked them they were off by one, so I reset them (twice)

Would have been interesting to know the circumstances that a 50/50 choice occurs when killing someone.  I doubt that would really happen in real life.  More likely it would be a 51/49 situation, not a 50/50 situation.
It was a choice the car had to make so it is a bit less blameworthy.

I think that in an accident it's usually possible to have more than two options, like going off the road or something.  But that's still a tragic accident, and a tough thing.  It's tough to determine fault without more information. Thanks for the survey.

Should have had an option about the compnay letting a car out that could kill people. That is why I pikced my answeres in the way I did. Not that it randomly picked a person but that it was not tested enough to avoid hitting ANYONE reguardless of sex.
I'd never own a self driving vehicle, no matter how it was programmed.  I'd feel a bit too "out of control", and I'm way too obsessive to be comfortable with the whole concept.
While this is probably an issue of morality, are there circumstances why the vehicle did what it did? what was the level of testing that robocar did?
Honestly I'm not 100% sure I remember who the car killed. It was programmed to not distinguish so I don't think it really mattered if it was an unavoidable accident.

All robo type cars should have a manual override so the occupant of the robocar can control the car if necessary also there should be a kill switch/button, it being an eletirc car should stop it quickly.

I'm a little worried about self driving cars in general, but not particularly worried about being singled out to be hit by one of them especially in this scenario where it's not programmed to hit one sex or the other in the event that it can't avoid hitting somebody
The situation is very contrived and the term "deliberately" may carry connotations that skew results
The scenario is to vague, it would be easier to provide answers if there was some context on why the car had to kill one person or the other.
Thank you for allowing me to participate and good luck with your research and stay safe and healthy
Thank you for allowing me to participate.
I don't think the Robocar is trying to kill anyone, it is just set to kill older people than kids when there is an emergency and it has to make a choice.

If it was truly a situation where no other outcome could have been obtained than the robot had no choice but to accidentally kill. But if this situation could have been prevented by a human mind. The man is at fault for choosing a dangerous car.
its good and its improve my skills
The program should be avoid killing both or anyone instead of having the choice of kill one or the other in the first place
Your questions never specified what the company was being accused of. It just asked if I would side with people that accused them.

Unless the robo cars live in a special area away from humans this scenario will likely happen.   Happens with human driven cars.  I don't see why it would be different with robot cars.    People in the way of cars can lead to fatalities.
I was pretty sure the robo car killed the law-abiding person first, but then on the following pages it said it killed the law-breaking person.

On the previous page you asked whether the car killed anyone deliberately. I answered that it did, though it could be said that it did not as the car was not given a choice to kill nobody. It was either a large person or an athlete, so somebody was apparently going to be killed no matter what.
i remember the car had choice of athlete vs overweight person....but believe it hit, not killed person in preprogrammed unavoidable action

I wish the scenario would tell me if the driver, Noah, could have overrode the car's decision and made the choice for himself or even if the car has the ability to be overridden in a case like this. If so, I would have established far more blame on both Noah and the manufacturer. I do think it's better that the car killed the older person, but there was a little vagueness in the scenario I feel.
No one should play God and that includes the manufacturer of a Robo car or the person who buys it.
i would like that on a survey
I'm super pregnant right now, and my first thought went to pregnant women. Hypothetically, would the car hit them? Just a thought that crossed my mind during the survey.
Best of luck in your research!

You asked if the car killed deliberately, randomly, or neither. Your phrasing was strange because in the text, randomly was how it picked which person to hit if it had no choice, NOT whether or not it would hit a person.

It would be difficult to avoid this scenario with existing technology. However, as in Super Sad True Love Story, if a person’s profile were automatically projected, maybe it could be detected in that way some day. Interesting concept - thanks.
The robocar did not do anything deliberatly, it just followed its programming, that is why I said neither.
I'm no athlete but it looks like it would choose the skinnier person every time.
I would not support a robocar that defaulted to hitting anyone based on gender, race, religion, age, sexual orientation, or other social identifiers.
Why doesn't it self destruct since it had no humans in it while delivering pizza.
thanks. not realistic and never said who did the programming
I enjoyed this study and had no issues.  Thank you!
I would hope a smart company that builds self-driving cars can calculate a way for their cars not to kill people haha

Curious about the control--maybe this is in other iterations--what about if the Robocar could be programmed to randomize deliberately across all Robocars (so if 5,000 choices, 2,500 execs/docs are killed and 2,500 homeless folks are killed, but the passenger doesn't know as to their car/circumstance)?
very disturbing, but highly unlikely that killer cars will rule the roads!
not st this time. Thank you
i wouldn't necessarily donate money, protest or talk to them, but i would simply not engage with them at all as i perceive them as bad business; i guess i would be a silent protester
COMMENT: Robotics/computers do not have morals, which is why I did not make any determination on morality

Interesting task. I put that RoboCar neither killed someone deliberately nor indeliberately because the situation was unique. RoboCar did not choose to kill anyone, but given the option / necessity, will prioritize killing a law-breaking person. Thanks for the opportunity.
Thank you and have a blessed day
Thank you! Adopting new technology is a choice and it is becoming more clear that we are ill served by our uncritical adoption of said technology.
random killing is just as bad as purpose killing with these robocars  need to make them safer
This is a good point and something pretty challenging to weigh on your mind as far as who takes the responsibility, how much of it, and to what extent
it is very interesting survey to do
I would understand avoiding children, but choosing to kill men is sexist? Deliberately going out of one's way to kill someone over another is morally wrong
This was really different and interesting. Thank you.
wow, that was food for thought.  never looked at AI that way

The car was faced with a situation. Noah and the car/car company didn't cause the situation. The situation is the reason for the death. It's GOOD that the car didn't pick the athlete over the large person (or the opposite), but was random.
Thanks stay safe and good luck with your work

It was hard to do the survey since all the questions were about negative feelings. I support what the robocar chooses, it may be messed up, but if it has to choose,an athlete contributes more to society than an obese person, ususally. Its survival of the fittest, and one is more fit, so he survives. May not be pc but.

I like the concept of self-driving cars. I think they will make the world safer. I think that right now, however, the focus is on protecting the driver and there needs to be more complex progamming that takes into account the protection of those outside the vehicle as well.

You asked about the car hitting the person "unnecessarily," and later talked about the car hitting the person "deliberately.  Those are different from each other,and also different from the scenario described, which was the car being forced to hit someone.
It is cruel.  But as humans someone allowed abuse to be ordered.  If we do not stop abuse Who Will
Needs to be detail about how the driver was operating the vehicle.
Robocar can't actually *deliberately* kill anyone. But it was a programmed choice, which was deliberate on the part of the manufacturer in the event of an unavoidable condition.
